web_results.snippet: Cloves are the aromatic flower buds of a tree in the family Myrtaceae, Syzygium aromaticum. They are native to the Maluku Islands, or Moluccas, in Indonesia, and are commonly used as a spice, flavoring, or fragrance in consumer products, such as toothpaste, soaps, or cosmetics.

list.title: Flavor
list.snippet: Cloves have a strong, pungent flavor and a warm, sweet aroma.

list.title: Uses
list.snippet: Cloves are used in many cuisines around the world and are a key ingredient in spice blends like garam masala and pumpkin spice. They can be used to add flavor and aroma to both sweet and savory dishes, including curries, stews, baked goods, and beverages.

list.title: Safety
list.snippet: There isn't enough reliable information to know if taking clove in larger amounts is safe or what the side effects might be. When applied to the skin, clove oil or cream containing clove flower is possibly safe.

buttons.subtitle: What Kind Of Spice Is Cloves?
buttons.title: Cloves - McCormick Science Institute
buttons.snippet: Cloves are one of the most intensely flavored spices: high quality cloves contain 15-20% essential oil. The characteristic flavor of cloves mainly comes from the aromatic compound “eugenol” which comprises upwards of 85% of the essential oil composition. Cloves can also cause a numbing sensation in the mouth.
snippet_highlighted_words: one of the most intensely flavored spices

buttons.subtitle: What Does Clove Taste Like
buttons.title: What are Cloves and How Do You Eat Them? | Kids Are Great Cooks
buttons.snippet: Cloves have a strong, warm, somewhat spicy taste. Because of its strong flavor, smaller amounts of cloves are used in recipes. Cloves have a similar, but stronger taste than nutmeg. Ground cloves usually lose their flavor faster than freshly ground cloves.
